1061–1134":"1061–1134","1205":"1205","28 octobre 1134":"28 October 1134","1204":"1204","1124":"1124","1156":"1156","1134":"1134","1100":"1100","1120":"1120","1175":"1175","1096":"1096","1061":"1061","Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France","Preuilly, Vienne, Poitou, France":"Preuilly, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France","Preuilly-sur-Claise, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France":"Preuilly-sur-Claise, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pierre","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From New Testament Greek.  See  <b>Peter</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Pierre Preuilly was born in 1096, in Preuilly, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France as the son of Eschevard de Preuilly seigneur de Preuilly, Bossay et La Roche Posay. He had at least 4 sons with Dame Euphrosyne de Vendome. He died in 1156, in Preuilly-sur-Claise, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1096–1156":"1096–1156","–Male":"Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1120–1205":"1120–1205","1124–1204":"1124–1204","–1175":"–1175","1061–1134":"1061–1134","1205":"1205","28 octobre 1134":"28. oktoober 1134","1204":"1204","1124